@startuml DatabaseSharding

title High-Level Design: Database Sharding & Replication

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam componentStyle rectangle

component "Application\nService" as app #D5E8D4
component "Shard Router /\nProxy (e.g. Vitess)" as router #DDEEFF

package "Shard 0  (userIds 0–33%)" {
    database "Primary DB 0" as p0 #FFF2CC
    database "Replica DB 0a" as r0a #EEE
    database "Replica DB 0b" as r0b #EEE
}

package "Shard 1  (userIds 33–66%)" {
    database "Primary DB 1" as p1 #FFF2CC
    database "Replica DB 1a" as r1a #EEE
}

package "Shard 2  (userIds 66–100%)" {
    database "Primary DB 2" as p2 #FFF2CC
    database "Replica DB 2a" as r2a #EEE
}

app    --> router : Query (sharding key = userId)
router --> p0     : Write / strong-read (shard 0)
router --> p1     : Write / strong-read (shard 1)
router --> p2     : Write / strong-read (shard 2)

router --> r0a    : Eventual-read (shard 0)
router --> r1a    : Eventual-read (shard 1)
router --> r2a    : Eventual-read (shard 2)

p0 --> r0a : async replication
p0 --> r0b : async replication
p1 --> r1a : async replication
p2 --> r2a : async replication

note right of router
  **Sharding Strategies:**

  Hash Sharding
  • shard = hash(key) % N
  • Uniform distribution
  • Hard to range-query

  Range Sharding
  • shard by value range (A-M, N-Z)
  • Natural ordering
  • Hot-spot risk

  Directory Sharding
  • Lookup table maps key → shard
  • Flexible, but lookup table is SPOF

  Geo Sharding
  • Shard by region/country
  • Reduces latency for regional data
end note

note bottom of p0
  **Replication Modes:**
  • Synchronous  — zero data loss, higher latency
  • Asynchronous — low latency, possible lag
  • Semi-sync     — at least one replica ACKs
end note

note right of app
  **Challenges:**
  • Cross-shard JOINs → denormalise / CQRS
  • Re-sharding → consistent hashing helps
  • Distributed transactions → 2PC / Sagas
  • Schema migrations → versioned migrations
end note

@enduml

